1. Introduction (Selecting and Loading the Datasets)¶

By considering my Student ID, I must predict the Consumer Price Index(2003=100)(TURKSAT). For this dataset, data is available up to 2003. Indeed, this situation enables us to create a model with the big dataset, but it is also a restriction for selecting independent variables for training a model. The reason behind this fact caused by limited datasets in the EVDS, namely there are few datasets(monthly) existing up to 2003. However, the model includes all the data related to the Consumer Price Index, and independent variables are selected by considering the availability of datasets.

First of all, which parameters are selected must be given to explain the reasons for selection. Dollar exchange rate(TP.DK.USD.A.YTL), Interest Rate(TP.KTF10), and Gold Reserve of the central bank(TP.AB.C2) are selected for analysis. By knowing the importance of the dollar index for all operations, the dollar index is the first index is set. In addition, all the processes are done with dollar. This fact can be observed at the new . Second Index is Interest Rate, and a lot of business depends on their operations to interest rate, which makes interest rate to a possible good independent variable to predict price index. This relevance also mentioned at the new. And the last index is the gold reverse. Gold Reserve is a good indicator for deciding policies for governments. Namely, by adding the gold reserve level, the model can explain small fluctuations in the price index rather than predicting the general trend. How the gold reserve is related to government policy can be obtained by the new.

Namely, all the datasets for prediction are relevant to the target variable somehow. Main aim of homework is to create a model to predict feature Price Index. And before creating the model, relevancy of the indexes will be approved by visualization and finding correlations. After that, a model will be created and evaluated by looking fundamental paramaters. In other words, our first aim to find out relevancy of research question which can be listed as:

  • Is there any natural relationship between the Dollar Currency Rate and Price Index?
  • A lot of things in production is dependent on the raw material. Does it cause a strong relation between the Dollar Currency Rate and Price Index?
  • Interest rate is one of the key factors for determined the production volume of countries. In addition, it can affect the behavior of people and manufacturers. Namely, the interest rate has multiple perspectives. So, is there any relation between the price index and interest rate?
  • Gold Reserve a good indicator of how governments make policy. Namely, the policy must be in harmony with the gold reserve in the central bank. So, do these policies have an impact on the revealed price index in Turkey?
  • Are all the founded resources mentioned in the introduction valid for Turkey?

After achieved first aim, second aim is to create a model without over-fitting or biased. After achieved these 2 goals, Consumer Price Index at 2020-12 will be predicted and compared with the actual value.

Lastly, a line plot with normalized values for datasets is established. In other words, it is impossible to compare and observe the values of datasets with actual values because they don't have the same unit (type) of values.

In general, by looking at all the line plots, it can be said that there are similarities between the price index and dollar rate and some similarities in terms of fluctuations. This situation is one of the good indicators for thinking there is relevancy between the determined parameters.

7. Model¶

In [70]:
dt=as.data.table(df_ts)

Because of the limited dataset, the model can have overfitting in the determined values. In order to overcome this issue(at least check the over-fitting), the dataset can be divided into 2 different datasets. One of them will be a training dataset that can be used for creating the model. After that, the model can predict the target values in the test dataset. These predictions will be evaluated from different perspectives to obtain the accuracy of the model. Indeed, subsetting can be made in different ways, but our aim is to predict the price index in the recent time period. So, the train set includes data before 2018 and the test data includes the rest. The main applied rule for the size of datasets is that 80% of the data allocated for training datasets. And the rest assigned as test dataset.

In [71]:
train=subset(dt,index<"2018-01-01")
test=subset(dt,index>="2018-01-01")

	Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation of order up to 10

data:  Residuals

It can be said that residuals distribution resembles normal by looking at the count plot. In addition, the mean of residuals is close to zero, which is also a desired feature for the model's residuals. There is a 2 problem, one of them is that there is autocorrelation between the residuals(LM test = 137.87, df = 10, p-value < 2.2e-16), especially for lag 1 and lag 12(compared to sequential lags). So, Lag 1 and Lag 12 can be good independent variables for predicting the price index(target value). The other problem is non-stationary variance in the residuals. But this problem must be checked again in a new model after added determined new independent features.

In the new model, the adjusted R-squared value is improved. However, 0.9973 can be an indicator of over-fitting in the training dataset, but the model will also be evaluated in the test dataset. So, the over-fitting situation will be considered in the next section of the Homework. In addition, the biggest improvement is achieved in the Residual standard values of the model. Namely, Residual standard error decreased from 10.59 to 3.888. In addition, Min and Max value in the model for residuals is also decreased nearly to 30% of the previous model. In general, there is an improvement in the model for prediction at least for the training dataset. Also, the interest rate became insignificant for the new model, but a different model trained without interest rate and checked in different perspectives. In the end, the interest rate is an important role especially for huge differences in the future time period, which can be approved by looking at the p-value of the parameter. P-value is too close to 0.1 and this situation enables us to keep this parameter in the model. Again, residual must be evaluated by using checkresidual function.

In [77]:
checkresiduals(fit1)

	Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation of order up to 10

data:  Residuals
LM test = 35.187, df = 10, p-value = 0.000116

Again, the distribution of residual resembles a normal distribution, which is a good indicator for the new model. In addition, Autocorrelation decreased a lot after adding lagged values. Still, there is autocorrelation between the residuals but it is much less than the previous model's residuals. This fact can be obtained by looking Breusch-Godfrey test of these 2 models. There is a huge improvement in terms of autocorrelation. Moreover, autocorrelation controlled with different order up values. All of them smaller than the previous model, so it can be said that there is an improvement in terms of autocorrelation. Lastly, the residuals plot has 2 important pieces of information. The first one is that mean of the residuals is close to zero, which is the desired feature for the model. The second one is constant variance in the residuals. In this perspective, it is hard to say that there is stationarity in the variance of residuals. Nevertheless, the variance didn't differentiate too much. So, the model can be assumed as acceptable for future predictions.

Lastly, month information doesn't seem required for the model. Nevertheless, month information is added to a different model as factor information. All the check processes applied to this new model. However, there is no improvement in the model achieved. But also, these new independent variables can cause an over-fitting by considering the input size of the model. Namely, 11 new features aren't reasonable to add to the model, and all the executions are removed to homework to make it more clear and understandable.

10. Conclusion¶

Much as there are some researches related to determined questions none of them executed their analysis in Turkey. Namely, obtained conclusions may not be valid in different regions. In addition, all the researches made separately for determined datasets. In this analysis, all the determined analyzed simultaneously with datasets in Turkey. After all, determined questions are answered. What obtained and answered can be listed as follows:

  • Resources mentioned in the intrıduction part is also valid for Turkey.
  • There are relevancy between the researched parameters.
  • Relevance between the parameters are not existing for an increasing trend for all independent variables. But for explaining fluctuations in values of the price index, all of them have an important role.
  • All the datasets are somehow correlated.

After approved the relevancy of the datasets somehow, a model created by just adding the independent variable that determined. In this model, there was relevancy between the residuals. This information obtained in 2 different tools, ACF and Breusch-Godfrey are these 2 tools. In order to decrease these autocorrelations in the residuals, lag 1 and lag 12 value of price index added to the model. Why month information didn't be added to model avoid to over-fitting situation occurring the limited size of training datasets. After added these 2 features, the R-squared value became higher and residual error decreased. But also, autocorrelation in the residuals are decreased and other fundamental requirements for linear regression are satisfied.

Lastly, the created model's performance checked with the test dataset. All the possible check tools gave good results related to the model. 2020-12 was predicted by the determined model and compared to the actual price index. There is a 13.8507 difference in the actual and predicted value. However, this situation is caused by the smoothness in the predictions of the model, which is a desired feature in the limited size of training datasets, and the price index must have been affected by the corona virus situation. Values related to the corona virus cannot be added to the model because it emerged in the last year and doesn't improve the model.
